    "abstract": "<jats:title>Abstract</jats:title>\n                <jats:p>\n                  Long COVID frequently presents with persistent neurological symptoms, including cognitive impairment, fatigue, and sleep disturbances; however, its underlying mechanisms remain unclear. Here, we show that SARS-CoV-2 infection induces lasting cortical neuronal injury and hypothalamic orexin (hypocretin) dysfunction\n                  <jats:italic>in vivo</jats:italic>\n                  . In K18-hACE2 and wild-type BALB/c mice, viral RNA persisted in the brain and coincided with focal loss of Neuronal Nuclei (NeuN)-positive cortical neurones beyond acute infection. SARS-CoV-2, but not the influenza A virus, triggered rapid and sustained suppression of hypothalamic orexin expression, defining a virus-specific neuropathological signature. Considering the downregulation of orexin and focal cortical NeuN expression, we showed that augmenting orexin signalling using recombinant orexin-A/B restored NeuN expression\n                  <jats:italic>in vitro</jats:italic>\n                  and\n                  <jats:italic>in vivo</jats:italic>\n                  . Overall, these findings identify the orexin system as a selective neural vulnerability to SARS-CoV-2 and define orexinergic circuit disruption as a mechanistic axis underlying the neurological manifestations of Long COVID.\n                </jats:p>",
